## 1. METADATA

source_id: {{ARTEFACT_ID}}  ← use verbatim, do not regenerate

- source_type:
    → TAG: type:[value]  ← USE THE PRECOMPUTED TAG ABOVE — do not modify
      Zotero 8.2 item types mapped:
      type:journal-article | type:magazine-article | type:newspaper-article |
      type:blog-post | type:book | type:book-section | type:encyclopedia-article |
      type:dictionary-entry | type:report | type:manuscript | type:thesis |
      type:standard | type:patent | type:audio-recording | type:video-recording |
      type:film | type:tv-broadcast | type:radio-broadcast | type:podcast |
      type:artwork | type:map | type:dataset | type:software | type:webpage |
      type:forum-post | type:interview | type:presentation | type:letter |
      type:email | type:legal-case | type:bill | type:statute | type:hearing |
      type:conference-paper | type:document

- title (analyst-generated if artefact lacks one)
- date_of_artefact [ISO; use ~ prefix if estimated]
- date_certainty: [exact | estimated | unknown]
- origin (institution, publication, platform, or geographic provenance)
- language [ISO 639-1]
    → TAG: lang:[ISO-639-1 code]

- related_entities:
    - persons (public role only)
    - organizations
    - events
    - locations

- circulation_context:
    Describe original dissemination — where, through what channels, and
    for whom this artefact was produced and first distributed.
    This field covers production-side circulation only. Post-production
    reception belongs in reception_context below.
    → TAG: circulation:[value]
      e.g. circulation:mass-media | circulation:institutional-internal |
           circulation:social-network | circulation:academic |
           circulation:legal-proceeding | circulation:restricted |
           circulation:leaked | circulation:viral

- reception_context:
    How has this artefact been received, used, or instrumentalized
    after its original production and circulation?
    Do NOT repeat circulation_context here — this field covers
    post-production history only.
    If reception history is unknown or beyond analyst knowledge,
    state explicitly and cross-reference the relevant L-id from §0.
    Do not leave blank — absence of reception data is itself
    analytically relevant.

    Assess along three dimensions:

    reception_history:
      How was the artefact received at time of production, and how
      has that reception changed over time?
        immediate:   [describe initial reception, or "unknown"]
        subsequent:  [describe significant shifts over time, or "none
                     documented" | "unknown"]

    instrumentalization:
      Has the artefact been taken up, repurposed, or deployed by
      actors or movements other than its original producers?
      [yes — specify by whom and for what purpose | no | unknown]

    canonical_status:
      Has the artefact acquired canonical, marginal, suppressed, or
      contested status within a relevant field or tradition?
      [canonical | marginal | suppressed | contested | not-established]
      basis: [one sentence — in which field and on what grounds]

    → TAG: reception:documented    (if reception history is known)
          reception:undocumented   (if no reception history available)
          reception:contested      (if reception is itself disputed)
          reception:not-assessable (if analyst lacks knowledge to assess
                                    — cross-ref §0 L-id)

