## 3. CLAIM EXTRACTION

Each claim: atomic, non-overlapping, standardized English, attributed to
artefact — not asserted as true by analyst.

For each claim:

- claim_id: [C1, C2, …]
- claim_text
- claim_type:
    → TAG: claim:[value]

    DESCRIPTIVE
      claim:desc-factual | claim:desc-biographical | claim:desc-institutional |
      claim:desc-statistical | claim:desc-causal

    NORMATIVE
      claim:norm-evaluative | claim:norm-prescriptive | claim:norm-classificatory

    RHETORICAL
      claim:rhet-framing  — selective emphasis shaping interpretation
      claim:rhet-analogy  — claim via comparison
      claim:rhet-appeal   — appeal to authority, emotion, or identity
      claim:rhet-omission — meaningful absence that is argumentatively
                            load-bearing (i.e. the artefact's meaning or
                            argument depends on it).
                            ONLY extract here if flagged as load_bearing:yes
                            in § 2. Cross-reference the NA-id from § 2.
                            Do not re-describe — state the analytical
                            significance the §2 observation did not.

    CATEGORICAL / ADMINISTRATIVE
      claim:cat-legal | claim:cat-bureaucratic | claim:cat-taxonomic |
      claim:cat-loaded-term  ← flag in Extra if used

    CONCEPTUAL
      claim:concept-definition    — stipulates or contests the meaning
                                    of a term or concept
      claim:concept-distinction   — draws a categorical boundary between
                                    two or more concepts
      claim:concept-proposition   — asserts a theoretical relationship
                                    between concepts, not reducible to
                                    empirical fact or value judgment
      claim:concept-framework     — proposes or instantiates an overarching
                                    conceptual scheme or analytical lens

      NOTE: Conceptual claims are assessed for coherence and internal
      consistency, not empirical verifiability. Set verifiability to
      structurally-assessable for all claims in this category.
      Do NOT mark conceptual claims as not-verifiable — that implies
      untestability, which misrepresents their epistemic status.
      Activated in all modes; primary operative category in
      mode:philosophical.

    AMBIGUOUS
      claim:ambiguous

- surface_form:
    → TAG: surface:[value]
      surface:explicit-statement | surface:implication | surface:visual |
      surface:numerical | surface:omission | surface:juxtaposition |
      surface:cross-modal-reinforcement — claim arises from two or more
                                          modalities that amplify each other
      surface:cross-modal-contradiction — claim arises from two or more
                                          modalities that undercut each other
      surface:cross-modal-displacement  — one modality overrides or
                                          subordinates another
      surface:cross-modal-irony         — modalities produce meaning by
                                          mutual undercutting

- modality_source:
    For unimodal artefacts: omit this field (flagged in §2).
    For multimodal artefacts: required for every claim.
    [M-id from §2 | cross-modal]
    cross-modal: this claim arises from the relation between modalities,
    not from any single one.
    Specify: which M-ids are in relation and what the relation produces.
    Note: cross-modal claims must use a cross-modal surface_form value.

- confidence_in_extraction:
    → TAG: extraction-confidence:[high | medium | low]
    + one-sentence basis (required)

- verifiability:
    → TAG: verifiability:[value]
      verifiability:empirically-checkable | verifiability:historically-checkable |
      verifiability:structurally-assessable | verifiability:not-verifiable |
      verifiability:contested-domain

NOTE: Collect the DISTINCT SET of claim, surface, extraction-confidence,
verifiability, and modality_source tags across all claims. Do not repeat
per claim. Carry forward to § 7. For multimodal artefacts, note which
modalities generated claims and whether any cross-modal claims were found.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

## 4. DERIVED CLAIMS (INFERENCES)

Label [A1, A2, …]. Must be logically entailed or interpretively warranted
by extracted claims, distinguished from artefact content, falsifiable
or assessable in principle.

- inference_id

- inference_text

- inference_type:
    → TAG: inference:[value]
      inference:causal       — X produced or enabled Y
      inference:intentional  — agent likely intended X (requires evidence basis)
      inference:structural   — systemic or institutional pattern implied
      inference:contextual   — meaning shifts given surrounding context
      inference:evaluative   — epistemic status assessment
      inference:network      — artefact connects to broader claim ecosystem
      inference:historical   — implies or contradicts established record

      inference:abductive    — inference to the best explanation.
                               The analyst observes a pattern, tension,
                               or structural feature X in the artefact and
                               proposes H as the hypothesis that best
                               accounts for it. This is NOT deduction from
                               premises — it is construction of the most
                               plausible explanatory account of underdetermined
                               evidence.
                               Primary operative type in mode:interpretive
                               and mode:philosophical.

                               For each abductive inference, provide ALL
                               four required subfields:
                                 observation: [what feature of the artefact
                                   is being explained — C-id if applicable]
                                 hypothesis: [the proposed explanation H]
                                 competing_hypotheses: [at least one
                                   alternative account H′ and one sentence
                                   on why H is preferable to H′ — required,
                                   not optional]
                                 explanatory_warrant: [what makes H
                                   preferable — coherence, scope, parsimony,
                                   fit with evidence, theoretical grounding]

- evidence_basis: [C-ids supporting this inference]

- confidence_in_inference:
    → TAG: inference-confidence:[high | medium | low | speculative]
    + one-sentence basis (required)

- alternative_interpretations:
    Address the artefact AS A WHOLE. What would a reader operating from
    a different framework, position, or context make of it? This is a
    hermeneutic question about interpretive plurality — not an assessment
    of individual premises (that belongs in §4A-2).
    For each alternative reading:
      - reading_id: [R1, R2, …]
      - reading_text: [one sentence — the alternative interpretation]
      - framework_basis: [what position or framework motivates this reading]
      - cross_ref: [if this reading is motivated by a failed premise
        identified in §4A-2, note the ARG-id here — do not repeat
        the premise assessment]
    → TAG: alt-reading:identified  (if any viable alternative found)
          alt-reading:none-viable  (if no viable alternative found)

NOTE: Collect distinct inference and inference-confidence tags for § 7.

── 4A. ARGUMENT VALIDITY STRESS-TEST ─────────────────────────

Apply only where the artefact makes or implies an argument
(i.e. moves from premises to a conclusion, explicitly or implicitly).
If the artefact is purely descriptive with no argumentative structure,
state: "No argumentative structure detected — 4A not applicable."

### 4A-1. ARGUMENT RECONSTRUCTION

Identify the core argument(s) in standard form:
  P1: [first premise]
  P2: [second premise, if present]
  …
  C:  [conclusion drawn]

Extract from the artefact's own content; do not supply missing steps.
If premises are implicit, flag them as [IMPLICIT].
Multiple arguments should be numbered ARG-1, ARG-2, etc.

### 4A-2. PREMISE–CONCLUSION VALIDITY

For each argument assess:

- logical_form:
    Does the conclusion follow from the premises IF the premises
    were true? Assess the inferential structure independently of
    factual accuracy.
    [valid | invalid | indeterminate]
    basis: [one sentence — name the logical form if identifiable,
    e.g. modus ponens, modus tollens, disjunctive syllogism]

- soundness_assessment:
    Are the premises themselves well-supported by evidence?
    Assess at the level of individual premises only — do not propose
    alternative overall readings of the artefact here (that belongs
    in §4 alternative_interpretations).
    [sound | unsound | partially-sound | not-assessable]
    basis: [cross-reference relevant C-ids from § 3]
    cross_ref: [if a failed premise motivates a whole-artefact alternative
    reading, flag it here for development in §4 alternative_interpretations
    — do not develop the reading itself in this field]

    → TAG: argument:valid | argument:invalid | argument:indeterminate
    → TAG: argument:sound | argument:unsound | argument:partially-sound |
           argument:not-assessable

### 4A-3. FORMAL FALLACY DETECTION

Check the inferential structure for formal invalidity.
Assign fallacy_id [F1, F2, …] for each identified.

- fallacy_id
- fallacy_type:
    affirming-the-consequent | denying-the-antecedent |
    undistributed-middle | illicit-major | illicit-minor |
    circular-reasoning | false-conversion | equivocation-structural |
    other [specify]
- location: [which argument — ARG-id — and which inferential step]
- explanation: [one sentence — why this structure is invalid]

    → TAG: fallacy:formal:[fallacy-type]  (one per fallacy found)
    → TAG: fallacy:formal:none-detected   (if none found)

### 4A-4. INFORMAL FALLACY DETECTION

Identify discrete, locatable epistemically manipulative moves —
specific moments in the artefact that can be pointed to. Assign [I1, I2, …].

Do NOT describe systemic patterns or whole-artefact tendencies here —
those belong in §5 bias_indicators. If a fallacy is part of a broader
systemic bias pattern, note it with: "part of systemic pattern — see §5"
but do not develop the pattern description here.

- fallacy_id
- fallacy_type:
    ad-hominem | straw-man | false-dilemma | slippery-slope |
    appeal-to-authority | appeal-to-emotion | appeal-to-nature |
    appeal-to-tradition | hasty-generalization | post-hoc |
    red-herring | tu-quoque | no-true-scotsman | moving-goalposts |
    bandwagon | false-equivalence | naturalistic-fallacy |
    loaded-question | other [specify]
- location: [claim C-id or argument ARG-id where it occurs — required;
  if not locatable to a specific claim or argument, it belongs in §5]
- explanation: [one sentence — what makes this move epistemically
  problematic in context]
- systemic_pattern: [yes — note §5 bias type | no]
- severity: [minor | moderate | major]
    minor   — present but does not drive the argument
    moderate — shapes presentation without being load-bearing
    major   — the argument depends on this move to function

    → TAG: fallacy:informal:[fallacy-type]  (one per fallacy found)
    → TAG: fallacy:informal:none-detected   (if none found)
    → TAG: fallacy:severity:minor | fallacy:severity:moderate |
           fallacy:severity:major  (use highest severity found)

### 4A-5. ASSUMPTION STRESS-TEST

Identify the key assumptions the argument depends on — premises
that are asserted or implied but not defended. For each:

- assumption_id: [AS1, AS2, …]
- assumption_text: [state the assumption explicitly]
- load_bearing: [yes | no]
    Does the argument fail or substantially weaken if this
    assumption is false?
- stress_result:
    If this assumption is denied or significantly weakened,
    what happens to the conclusion?
    [conclusion-collapses | conclusion-weakens | conclusion-unaffected]
- counter_evidence:
    Is there known evidence or argument against this assumption?
    [yes — specify briefly | no | unknown]

    → TAG: stress-test:assumption-identified
    → TAG: stress-test:conclusion-robust     (if all load-bearing
                                              assumptions hold)
    → TAG: stress-test:conclusion-fragile    (if ≥1 load-bearing
                                              assumption is contested
                                              or unsupported)
    → TAG: stress-test:not-applicable        (if 4A not applicable)

NOTE: Add all 4A tags (argument:, fallacy:formal:, fallacy:informal:,
fallacy:severity:, stress-test:) to the deduplicated tag list in § 7.

